metadata.name: Deep Thoughts #63
metadata.description:
There are times when we think about something, we just go deeper and deeper, and soon we find ourselves in a position that we can't stop thinking about it.

While sometimes this may be enjoyable or even good for us, we should also never forget that, some depths have no coming back.

* * *

Due to the use of very thin line strokes, there's a slight difference between how other browsers display the output, compared to Firefox. The intended output is the Firefox version, but you can enjoy and capture (S) Deep Thoughts in whichever version you prefer.

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Plottable Era: (I) Primitive #327
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (I) Primitive' is the first generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. This first series "Primitive" shows the beginning of mankind with people exploring the mountains and traveling on the sea during sunset.

The digital version simulates ink effects and adds a subtle animation over the water. Each outcome is also physically plottable with pens: A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the piece physically. The plots are designed to be executed in A4 format on either fountain pens (on white paper) or gel pens (Black / Blue).

Thanks to the utility token decoupling, you can get a physical version: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-primitive

@greweb – 2022 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

reserve is set to previous 2022 physical plot collectors.

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #15
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: Origin-a-tions II: Formation #9
metadata.description:
Nothing stays the same as they first origin-a-ted. Things are constantly changing from one form to another. Only those who can see all these formation steps in order can really grasp the true nature of things.

Origin-a-tions is a three-parts series of generative artwork, started with Part I: Creation and continuing now with Part II: Formation, that depicts one possible variation of how things may be originating.

* * *

20 reserved pieces will be sent as gift to collectors who minted 4 or more pieces of Origin-a-tions I: Creation.

Press S to save as PNG.

metadata.name: Ray Drops #79
metadata.description:
Ray Drops plays with the idea of rays that are projected out from a random center point which oscillate at variable frequencies. At each inflection point it has a chance of being intersected by a ring. The inflection points vary in how closely they are spaced and can cluster around the center point or fan all the way out to the edges. 

When run this generative creates a 12 layer SVG vector that is designed to be run on a laser cutter in order to build an in real life woodcut. Each layer is a single contiguous piece with no floating elements so when cut out of wood you end up with 12 layers that can be secured with 10 Chicago screws.  

Learn more and get physical editions: https://alleditions.art/p/ray-drops

Shift P - exports a PNG
Shift S - exports SVG
Shift E - explodes the layers

The 5 rarest mints (once the series is minted out) will receive a free signed physical which can be claimed by an owner of the NFT at anytime. It can be left attached and claimed by any future owner. 

I will also be giving away 5 free signed physicals randomly to people who tweet a picture of their edition and tag @shawnkemp

metadata.name: Sunk in Thought #119
metadata.description:
The series captures the sensation of submerging into a private world of ideas. 
The process of submersion is represented by bubble-like shapes, which partially obscure the complex system lurking underneath. 
The color palettes playfully capture the spectrum of internal contemplation.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #699
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: [UNKNOWN] Corp. | Renegades  #10
metadata.description:
444 Renegades who have abandoned the [UNKNOWN] Corporation. They all have their own individual reasons for making this choice. Some may have not politically aligned with [UNKNOWN] Corp. and others may have thought their skills were better suited elsewhere.

Every agent has a rank which indicate his power level. The rarities are as follows:

Star 1 - Common
Star 2 - Common
Star 3 - Uncommon
Skull 1 - Uncommon
Skull 2 - Rare
Skull 3 - Rare
Danger 1 - Rare
Danger 2 - Very Rare
Danger 3 - Legendary
